answers.body_markdown:
Most likely you are converting some characters such as `&lt;` and `&gt;` into HTML entities, and naturally, a query contains `&lt;abc@abcs.com&gt;` will never match a text `&amp;lt;abc@abcs.com&amp;gt;`.

The problem is, this is only a guess, and nobody can tell you what the actual issue is, because it is **your** database, **your** input data and only **you** can find the issue. 

I wrote an article that explains [how to debug your PDO issues](https://phpdelusions.net/pdo/mcve). Basically you need to scrutinize both the data in the database and the input data to find the difference. And then eliminate the code that introduces it. A `bin2hex()` function would help, revealing all non-printable and converted characters, in both database and the input.

On a side note, but very important nevertheless: your prepared statement is a [cargo cult code](https://phpdelusions.net/pdo/cargo_cult_prepared_statement) that **protects nothing**. Here is how it **must** be:

    $sql = &#39;SELECT count(*) FROM inbox WHERE uid = ? AND from_email = ?&#39;; 
    $result = $link-&gt;prepare($sql); 
    $result-&gt;execute([$email_number,$email_f]); 
    $number_of_rows = $result-&gt;fetchColumn();

